Introduction ¶

Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending marketplace that helps in facilitating loans. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. This Sheet contains information about the dataset variables.

In [10]:
# converts to ordered categorical datatype
def convert_ordinal_dtype(ordinal_var_dict):
    for var in ordinal_var_dict:
        pd_ver = pd.__version__.split(".")
        if (int(pd_ver[0]) > 0) or (int(pd_ver[1]) >= 21): # v0.21 or later
            ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                        categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
            loan_data[var] = loan_data[var].astype(ordered_var)
        else: # pre-v0.21
            loan_data[var] = loan_data[var].astype('category', ordered = True,
                                                 categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

It contains 113937 rows and 81 columns. Most of the columns are numeric (float) with some in categories (ordered and unordered). Overall, the dataset needs to be cleaned as there are mixed datatypes in some columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

As an investor, my interest lies with who is likely to repay a loan and who are the major defaulters in loan repayment. I will be investigating factors that are responsible for defaulting in loan repayment.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Variables relating to income such as occupation,income range, employment status, debtToIncomeRatio and credit history will be of great help.

Asides from these two, 'Executive', 'Computer Programmer', 'Administrative Assistant', 'Teacher' are also popular.

Why do people borrow on Prosper?¶

def log_trans(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10,x)

For both 12 and 36 months term, the difference between EstimatedEffectiveYield and EstimatedReturn is quite high based on shape of the distribution of the boxplots. It turns out that long term loans(60months) tends to more profitable for an investor.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I explored relationships between some numerical and categorical variables. From the exploration, I observed that monthlyloanpayment and borrowerAPR are factors contributing to loan status. Some of the relationships observed are;

  • For defaulted loans, the monthly payment is quite high when compared to other loan status categories. Perhaps the possibility of not been able to keep up with payments. For completed loans, the distribution of monthly payments is positively skewed with an averagely low amount. However, the borrowerAPR for most completed loans is high while it is low for defaulted loans.
  • I also discovered that borrowers with part-time employment status pay more monthly payment and their borrowerAPR is high. I assume this is because they either prefer to take long-term loans and spread their monthly payments due to their employment status.
  • Long term loans have high borrowerAPR and high Estimated Returns.
  • The stated monthly income of loan defaulters is the lowest when compared to loans in good standing.
  • Doctors, Attorneys and Judges have the highest monthly stated income while the students categories have the least monthly stated income.
  • When I compared loan status with employment status, the distribution of the plot is almost similar for both completed and defaulted loans. Even though the range differs in both loan status categories, full-time employees are the highest loan defaulters and completers. I assume this is because of their employment status as they can be out of job anytime.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I decided to look at factors behind the ProsperRating so when compared with CreditScoreRangeUpper, there was a positive correlation. I want to imply that a good or high credit score increases the likelihood of being qualified for a loan with higher risk or rate involved.

Do higher/lower income earners defaults more?¶

Explore the relationship between incomeRange, loanStatus and TotalProsperLoans.

Because we have a lot of categories in the Loan status column. I want to focus on completed and defaulted loans for this analysis. Therefore, I will create a new column 'IsDefault'.

In [262]:
# categorize loans
def isLoanDefault(status):
    if status == 'Completed':
        val = 'no'
    elif status == 'Defaulted':
        val = 'yes'
    else:
        val = 'maybe'
    return val

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The ProsperRating strengthened the estimated return as it proves to be a useful measure in categorizing the loan type for investors. I also noticed that as income increases so does the number of prosper loans received by borrowers increases.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Most people request for loans for debt consolidation across the year. An interesting find is that people take out high loans to purchase Recreation Vehicles during the third Quarter of the year and also for Weddings in the last quarter of the year.

Conclusions¶

From the analysis, I discovered reasons why people take loans. Debt Consolidation is by far the most reason and a look into the borrowers state implies most borrowers reside in California, a state with high cost of living. Also long term loan tends to be more favourable for investors as it has higher returns. For loan defaulters, I could not deduce who they are since across the income ranges, the number of completed loans vs defaulted loans appear to be balanced. I would expect that as income increases, loans should reduce but it is otherwise.
